│ Understanding the Issue:\nThe SLP vectorizer transforms a pair of scalar      │
│ operations involving i64 abs calls followed by trunc to i32 into a vector     │
│ sequence that computes i32 abs on the vectorized i32 mul results. In doing    │
│ so, it also flips the second argument of the abs intrinsic from true to false │
│ when reducing bitwidth. This changes semantics and causes a                   │
│ miscompile.\n\nSpecifically, original IR:\n- m1/m2 = mul of zext nneg i32 by  │
│ constant -> results are non-negative i64 with nuw/nsw.\n- a1/a2 =             │
│ llvm.abs.i64(m1/m2, true) -> abs is a no-op on non-negative values.\n- t1/t2  │
│ = trunc i64 to i32 -> source is simply low 32bits of non-negative             │
│ i64.\n\nTransformed IR:\n- performs i32 mul (wrapping), producing possibly    │
│ negative values,\n- applies llvm.abs.v2i32 with second arg false, so abs      │
│ operates in 32-bit domain and produces different values than trunc of i64     │
│ abs. Alive2 shows mismatch.\n\n2. Analyzing opt's Log:\n- The SLP logs show   │
│ vectorization of the truncs, abs calls, muls, zexts, and adds.\n- The emitted │
│ target uses @llvm.abs.v2i32(..., i1 false), whereas the source had            │
│ @llvm.abs.i64(..., i1 true).\n- The mismatch example demonstrates that        │
│ trunc(abs(i64(prod))) != abs(i32(prod32)) due to 32-bit wrap/abs behavior.\n- │
│ The log points to BoUpSLP::vectorizeTree(Call) path where abs gets vectorized │
│ and the scalar arg is set to false when MinBWs decides to reduce              │
│ bitwidth.\n\nRelevant code section:\nAt lines 15244-15249:\n  // if decided   │
│ to reduce bitwidth of abs intrinsic, it second argument\n  // must be set     │
│ false (do not return poison, if value issigned min).\n  if (ID ==             │
│ Intrinsic::abs && It != MinBWs.end() &&\n      It->second.first <             │
│ DL->getTypeSizeInBits(CEI->getType()))\n    ScalarArg =                       │
│ Builder.getFalse();\n\nThis unconditionally overrides the abs's poison-on-min │
│ flag to false when reducing bitwidth, which changes semantics compared to the │
│ original flag (true) and breaks cases where the operand's non-negativity      │
│ makes abs a no-op.\n\n3. Root Cause Analysis:\n- The vectorizer reduces the   │
│ bitwidth of the abs operation and forces the second argument to false. In our │
│ case, the original flag is true (poison on INT_MIN). For non-negative inputs  │
│ (like ours), abs is an identity. Reducing bitwidth and flipping the flag      │
│ changes the operation to abs on a potentially negative i32 value with flag    │
│ false, producing a different result than trunc of the i64 value.\n- The       │
│ assumption in the comment is unsafe: \"must be set false\" does not hold in   │
│ general. We must preserve the original semantics, or, if we can prove the abs │
│ input is non-negative, we can elide abs entirely. At minimum, do not flip the │
│ flag unconditionally.\n\n4. Proposed Edit Point(s):\n- Edit the logic at      │
│ lines 15244-15249 in llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/SLPVectorizer.cpp to       │
│ preserve the original abs intrinsic's second argument when reducing bitwidth, │
│ unless we can prove the operand is non-negative (in which case we should keep │
│ it as true or remove abs). A minimal and safe fix is to stop overriding it to │
│ false.\n\nConcrete change:\nReplace the block that sets ScalarArg =           │
│ Builder.getFalse() with code that preserves the original flag:\n\nCurrent:\n  │
│ // if decided to reduce bitwidth of abs intrinsic, it second argument\n  //   │
│ must be set false (do not return poison, if value issigned min).\n  if (ID == │
│ Intrinsic::abs && It != MinBWs.end() &&\n      It->second.first <             │
│ DL->getTypeSizeInBits(CEI->getType()))\n    ScalarArg =                       │
│ Builder.getFalse();\n\nFix:\n  // When reducing bitwidth of abs intrinsic,    │
│ preserve the original poison-on-min flag.\n  // Flipping to false changes     │
│ semantics and can miscompile if the operand is non-negative\n  // or          │
│ otherwise relies on the original 'true' behavior.\n  if (ID == Intrinsic::abs │
│ && It != MinBWs.end() &&\n      It->second.first <                            │
│ DL->getTypeSizeInBits(CEI->getType())) {\n    // Keep the original flag       │
│ operand as is.\n    ScalarArg = CEI->getArgOperand(I);\n    // Optionally, if │
│ the abs operand is known non-negative, we could later elide abs,\n    // but  │
│ do not change the flag here.\n  }\n\nThis ensures @llvm.abs.vNi32 will be     │
│ called with the same second argument as the original, avoiding the mismatch   │
│ in the reproducer. Further refinements could also detect non-negativity and   │
│ drop abs entirely, but the minimal fix restores correctness.\n\n5.            │
│ Conclusion:\nThe miscompile stems from the SLP vectorizer unconditionally     │
│ setting the abs intrinsic's second argument to false when reducing bitwidth,  │
│ altering semantics. Preserving the original flag fixes the issue and makes    │
│ the vectorized result match the scalar version. This change prevents          │
│ incorrect results like the one shown by Alive2 and maintains consistency with │
│ original IR semantics during vectorization."})                                │
