│ ### Root Cause Analysis ###                                                   │
│                                                                               │
│ -------------------- BEGIN --------------------                               │
│ 1. Understanding the Issue:                                                   │
│ The SLP vectorizer transforms a pair of scalar operations involving i64 abs   │
│ calls followed by trunc to i32 into a vector sequence that computes i32 abs   │
│ on the vectorized i32 mul results. In doing so, it also flips the second      │
│ argument of the abs intrinsic from true to false when reducing bitwidth. This │
│ changes semantics and causes a miscompile.                                    │
│                                                                               │
│ Specifically, original IR:                                                    │
│ - m1/m2 = mul of zext nneg i32 by constant -> results are non-negative i64    │
│ with nuw/nsw.                                                                 │
│ - a1/a2 = llvm.abs.i64(m1/m2, true) -> abs is a no-op on non-negative values. │
│ - t1/t2 = trunc i64 to i32 -> source is simply low 32bits of non-negative     │
│ i64.                                                                          │
│                                                                               │
│ Transformed IR:                                                               │
│ - performs i32 mul (wrapping), producing possibly negative values,            │
│ - applies llvm.abs.v2i32 with second arg false, so abs operates in 32-bit     │
│ domain and produces different values than trunc of i64 abs. Alive2 shows      │
│ mismatch.                                                                     │
│                                                                               │
│ 2. Analyzing opt's Log:                                                       │
│ - The SLP logs show vectorization of the truncs, abs calls, muls, zexts, and  │
│ adds.                                                                         │
│ - The emitted target uses @llvm.abs.v2i32(..., i1 false), whereas the source  │
│ had @llvm.abs.i64(..., i1 true).                                              │
│ - The mismatch example demonstrates that trunc(abs(i64(prod))) !=             │
│ abs(i32(prod32)) due to 32-bit wrap/abs behavior.                             │
│ - The log points to BoUpSLP::vectorizeTree(Call) path where abs gets          │
│ vectorized and the scalar arg is set to false when MinBWs decides to reduce   │
│ bitwidth.                                                                     │
│                                                                               │
│ Relevant code section:                                                        │
│ At lines 15244-15249:                                                         │
│   // if decided to reduce bitwidth of abs intrinsic, it second argument       │
│   // must be set false (do not return poison, if value issigned min).         │
│   if (ID == Intrinsic::abs && It != MinBWs.end() &&                           │
│       It->second.first < DL->getTypeSizeInBits(CEI->getType()))               │
│     ScalarArg = Builder.getFalse();                                           │
│                                                                               │
│ This unconditionally overrides the abs's poison-on-min flag to false when     │
│ reducing bitwidth, which changes semantics compared to the original flag      │
│ (true) and breaks cases where the operand's non-negativity makes abs a no-op. │
│                                                                               │
│ 3. Root Cause Analysis:                                                       │
│ - The vectorizer reduces the bitwidth of the abs operation and forces the     │
│ second argument to false. In our case, the original flag is true (poison on   │
│ INT_MIN). For non-negative inputs (like ours), abs is an identity. Reducing   │
│ bitwidth and flipping the flag changes the operation to abs on a potentially  │
│ negative i32 value with flag false, producing a different result than trunc   │
│ of the i64 value.                                                             │
│ - The assumption in the comment is unsafe: "must be set false" does not hold  │
│ in general. We must preserve the original semantics, or, if we can prove the  │
│ abs input is non-negative, we can elide abs entirely. At minimum, do not flip │
│ the flag unconditionally.                                                     │
│                                                                               │
│ 4. Proposed Edit Point(s):                                                    │
│ - Edit the logic at lines 15244-15249 in                                      │
│ llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/SLPVectorizer.cpp to preserve the original abs  │
│ intrinsic's second argument when reducing bitwidth, unless we can prove the   │
│ operand is non-negative (in which case we should keep it as true or remove    │
│ abs). A minimal and safe fix is to stop overriding it to false.               │
│                                                                               │
│ Concrete change:                                                              │
│ Replace the block that sets ScalarArg = Builder.getFalse() with code that     │
│ preserves the original flag:                                                  │
│                                                                               │
│ Current:                                                                      │
│   // if decided to reduce bitwidth of abs intrinsic, it second argument       │
│   // must be set false (do not return poison, if value issigned min).         │
│   if (ID == Intrinsic::abs && It != MinBWs.end() &&                           │
│       It->second.first < DL->getTypeSizeInBits(CEI->getType()))               │
│     ScalarArg = Builder.getFalse();                                           │
│                                                                               │
│ Fix:                                                                          │
│   // When reducing bitwidth of abs intrinsic, preserve the original           │
│ poison-on-min flag.                                                           │
│   // Flipping to false changes semantics and can miscompile if the operand is │
│ non-negative                                                                  │
│   // or otherwise relies on the original 'true' behavior.                     │
│   if (ID == Intrinsic::abs && It != MinBWs.end() &&                           │
│       It->second.first < DL->getTypeSizeInBits(CEI->getType())) {             │
│     // Keep the original flag operand as is.                                  │
│     ScalarArg = CEI->getArgOperand(I);                                        │
│     // Optionally, if the abs operand is known non-negative, we could later   │
│ elide abs,                                                                    │
│     // but do not change the flag here.                                       │
│   }                                                                           │
│                                                                               │
│ This ensures @llvm.abs.vNi32 will be called with the same second argument as  │
│ the original, avoiding the mismatch in the reproducer. Further refinements    │
│ could also detect non-negativity and drop abs entirely, but the minimal fix   │
│ restores correctness.                                                         │
│                                                                               │
│ 5. Conclusion:                                                                │
│ The miscompile stems from the SLP vectorizer unconditionally setting the abs  │
│ intrinsic's second argument to false when reducing bitwidth, altering         │
│ semantics. Preserving the original flag fixes the issue and makes the         │
│ vectorized result match the scalar version. This change prevents incorrect    │
│ results like the one shown by Alive2 and maintains consistency with original  │
│ IR semantics during vectorization.                                            │
